// TEST: exec_int_div_large
// EXPECT: output "4503599627370496;1"
// EXPECT: targets python, rust, go
//
// DQ23 (§3.6) precision guard: integer division/modulo must stay in exact
// integer arithmetic and NOT route through float true-division.
// `9007199254740993` is `2^53 + 1` — the first odd integer not exactly
// representable as an IEEE-754 double (it rounds to `2^53`). The remainder is the
// discriminator: the exact integer `(2^53+1) % 2 == 1`, but a float route — most
// dangerously Python's `int(a / b)`, which the toward-zero helper deliberately
// avoids — first rounds `2^53+1` to the even `2^53`, after which the odd bit is
// gone and `% 2` reads `0`. A passing `;1` proves the Python (and Rust/Go)
// lowering kept the low bit in exact integer arithmetic.
// `(2^53+1) / 2 == 4503599627370496` (the truncated quotient).
//
// Restricted to `python, rust, go`: JS/TS map `Int` to the IEEE-754 `number`,
// which cannot represent any integer above `2^53` at all — the *literal*
// `9007199254740993` is already rounded to `2^53` at parse time, before any
// division, so the precision a 64-bit integer target preserves is structurally
// unavailable on `number`. (A BigInt-backed `Int` on JS/TS is a separate,
// DQ23-orthogonal concern.) The truncate-toward-zero behavior of the JS/TS
// integer `/` lowering within `number`'s safe range is covered by
// `exec_int_div_truncate` and `exec_int_mod_sign`.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public`.
module main

fn opaque(n: Int) -> Int {
  return n
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let big: Int = opaque(9007199254740993)
  let two: Int = opaque(2)
  println("${big / two};${big % two}")
}
